\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces The ScholarHub{} landing page at \url {https://scholarhub.space}. The hero positioning states the integration thesis directly: ``one workspace instead of five''. The interactive preview below the headline cycles through the discovery, library, and editor surfaces before sign-up.}}{5}{figure.caption.7}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.1}{\ignorespaces ScholarHub{}'s public pricing page at \url {scholarhub.space/pricing}. Three tiers cover the free, individual-pro, and bring-your-own-key segments. Pro is positioned at USD 15 per month, below the price of any single component of the conventional Overleaf--Zotero--ChatGPT stack.}}{17}{figure.caption.10}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.2}{\ignorespaces Tool positioning on the axes of integration breadth (horizontal) and AI grounding (vertical). ScholarHub{} occupies the upper-right quadrant where integration breadth and grounding are both high; no existing product currently operates in this quadrant.}}{18}{figure.caption.11}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces High-level architecture. The browser communicates with the system through an Nginx reverse proxy, which routes HTTP traffic to the FastAPI backend and WebSocket traffic to the Hocuspocus collaboration server. The principal persistence paths are shown: the backend writes to PostgreSQL with pgvector, and the collaboration server caches room state in Redis. Secondary connections (the backend also uses Redis for session caching, and the collaboration server periodically snapshots Y.Doc state to PostgreSQL) are described in the text below.}}{25}{figure.caption.12}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces AI orchestration loop. The model is called with the conversation history and the registered tool definitions. If the model emits a tool call, the orchestrator executes it, appends the result to the message history, and recalls the model. The loop terminates when the model produces a non-tool response, which is then streamed to the client.}}{29}{figure.caption.16}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces The discussion view inside a project. Channels organize threaded conversations (project-wide and paper-scoped); the AI agent participates as a regular channel member but is implemented as the tool-orchestrated agent described in this section. The model picker at the top right routes between OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and OpenRouter providers.}}{30}{figure.caption.17}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces Paper discovery in ScholarHub{} with results displayed. The query \emph {``arabic character-level BERT pretraining''} returns 20 deduplicated, relevance-ranked papers from seven sources in parallel (Crossref 20, ScienceDirect 20, OpenAlex 20, Europe PMC 20, CORE 9, arXiv 1, PubMed 0; Semantic Scholar was rate-limited and surfaces a Retry control). Each result shows its relevance score, source badge, year, venue, abstract excerpt, and one-click Add or Dismiss.}}{31}{figure.caption.19}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.5}{\ignorespaces Collaboration architecture. Clients connect to the Hocuspocus server over WebSocket. Document state is held in memory by Hocuspocus and replicated to Redis for cross-process consistency. Snapshots are persisted to PostgreSQL on a configurable interval. Logically, all clients participate in a single CRDT; physically, the server mediates message delivery for efficiency and authentication.}}{32}{figure.caption.20}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.6}{\ignorespaces Paper discovery architecture. The query builder normalizes the user query for each source's expected syntax. The source router dispatches in parallel. As results arrive, the deduplicator collapses identical works using a union-find structure keyed by DOI, arXiv ID, and normalized title. The reranker applies semantic reranking when configured. Results are streamed as Server-Sent Events.}}{33}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.7}{\ignorespaces The project library (References tab). Each entry shows title, authors, year, source, and a status indicator for AI ingestion (text extraction and embedding for retrieval). One-click actions are exposed for chat-with-paper, citation insertion into the active draft, and re-ingestion.}}{34}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.8}{\ignorespaces Project AI Settings dialog. The model picker exposes the full set of OpenRouter-routable models. The ``Share your API key with team members'' toggle allows a project owner to provide a single API key for all members, useful in supervised research settings where the supervisor pays for inference.}}{35}{figure.caption.23}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces Global dashboard. The first view after sign-in surfaces the user's project activity, quick links into discovery and the editor, and the entry point for creating a new project. The empty state shown here is what a fresh account encounters before any projects exist.}}{41}{figure.caption.26}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces Projects list. The user's owned and shared projects are shown as cards with title, description, member count, and last-activity timestamp. The list is the main navigation surface for switching between projects.}}{42}{figure.caption.27}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces Project overview view. The dashboard summarizes the project context (description, objectives, keywords), member list, paper and reference counts, and recent activity in a single page. Tab navigation switches between Overview, Papers, Discussion, and Library.}}{43}{figure.caption.28}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.4}{\ignorespaces New project modal. The user provides a title, description, keywords (added by Enter or comma), and one or more objectives. The objectives become the criteria that drive the AI assistant's project-grounded behaviour throughout the project lifetime.}}{44}{figure.caption.29}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.5}{\ignorespaces Project library, References sub-tab. The view lists papers the user has saved into the project from discovery or imported from an external reference manager (nine here). Each row exposes title, authors, venue, year, source database, an action menu, and per-paper Chat and Cite-in-Paper actions. The toolbar exposes List/Graph layouts and \texttt {.bib} export/import alongside the Zotero import entry point.}}{45}{figure.caption.30}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.6}{\ignorespaces Paper workspace view. Opening a research paper from the Papers list lands the user on a read-only summary that aggregates the paper's research goals (linked to project objectives), its attached references (citations pulled from the project library), the team with their roles, and the paper-level keywords. The \emph {Write} action in the top-right transitions to the LaTeX editor.}}{46}{figure.caption.31}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.7}{\ignorespaces Integrations panel in account settings. The two supported third-party integrations in the deployed system are exposed: \emph {OpenRouter} (a bring-your-own-key field that routes the project's AI calls through the user's own OpenRouter account; shown here in the \emph {Connected} state) and \emph {Zotero} (an API-key and user-ID pair that enables the reference-manager import flow). Both credentials are encrypted at rest.}}{47}{figure.caption.32}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.8}{\ignorespaces The collaborative LaTeX editor. The source pane on the left is bound to a Y.js \texttt {Y.Text} through \texttt {y-codemirror.next}; the PDF pane on the right shows the live compilation. The top toolbar exposes file/edit menus, citation insertion, formatting, and the AI assistant entry point. The image shows a live paper from the \emph {Arabic Character BERT} project deployed at \url {scholarhub.space}.}}{48}{figure.caption.33}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.9}{\ignorespaces The AI assistant sidebar inside the editor. The sidebar opens beside the PDF pane, hosts a tool-orchestrated agent (here using OpenAI GPT-5.2), and operates against the active paper's full context (LaTeX source, attached references, project objectives). Reasoning mode and chat-history controls are exposed in the header.}}{49}{figure.caption.34}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.10}{\ignorespaces Document history view. Each save (manual or auto) is a timestamped revision with character-count delta, change summary, and an optional label. The user can preview any past version, compare two versions, or restore. AI-generated initial versions are tagged so the provenance is preserved.}}{50}{figure.caption.35}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.11}{\ignorespaces Editor formatting and structural-insertion tools. The main toolbar exposes the most-used actions (\emph {Insert from References}, which pulls a citation from the project library directly into the cursor position, plus \emph {Figure} and \emph {Citation}); the overflow popover shown here groups the secondary actions: \emph {Table}, \emph {Bullet List}, \emph {Numbered List}, \emph {Hyperlink}, \emph {Cross Reference}, \emph {Toggle Comment}, and indent controls. Combined with the AI assistant, these are the principal authoring affordances.}}{51}{figure.caption.36}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.12}{\ignorespaces The file tree sidebar inside the editor. Four asset classes are exposed (TEX files, support files, figures, templates), each accepting drag-and-drop uploads. The lower pane derives a section outline from CodeMirror state and supports click-to-scroll navigation.}}{53}{figure.caption.38}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.13}{\ignorespaces Template library inside the file tree. Twenty-two pre-built venue templates are exposed for one-click application to the active document. The library covers NLP and ML conferences (ACL, NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR, IJCAI, AAAI, JMLR), computer vision (CVPR, ICCV, ECCV), ACM and IEEE venues (IEEE Conference, ACM CHI, KDD), and journals (Nature, PNAS, PLOS ONE, Springer LNCS, Elsevier, APA, Chicago/Turabian, plus a generic article default).}}{54}{figure.caption.39}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.14}{\ignorespaces Writing quality analysis sidebar. The analyzer scores the document, lists categorized issues with concrete suggestions (here: four missing standard sections), and reports document statistics including a normalized citations-per-thousand-words density. The target-venue dropdown switches between generic and venue-specific rule sets.}}{55}{figure.caption.40}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.15}{\ignorespaces Submission Package Builder dialog. The target venue dropdown exposes five publisher profiles (IEEE, ACM, Springer LNCS, Elsevier, arXiv). The dialog renders the selected venue's required document class, font size, abstract word limit, reference style, packages, and section structure; the \emph {Validate} and \emph {Build Package} actions check and assemble the submission-ready archive respectively.}}{56}{figure.caption.41}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.16}{\ignorespaces Sync Space: the in-project video meetings view. A live call is shown in the active state. The page header explains the value proposition (live call, persistent transcript, GPT-5 follow-ups for the team) and the per-call card exposes Join and End actions.}}{57}{figure.caption.43}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.17}{\ignorespaces The Daily.co prebuilt UI inside a Sync Space call. The room name is derived from the project's short identifier and the session UUID, and the meeting token is scoped to the project's membership. The recording layer routes audio into the transcription pipeline.}}{58}{figure.caption.44}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.18}{\ignorespaces Post-call state. After the call ends, the session is queued for transcription (\emph {Transcribing\dots }); once complete, the transcript and AI-generated meeting notes become available through the \emph {View details} button. Sessions can be cleared from the project history when no longer needed.}}{59}{figure.caption.45}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.19}{\ignorespaces Editor in the failed-compile state. The left pane shows the source with an undefined command at line~17 and an unclosed brace at line~18; the right pane retains the last successfully compiled PDF (so the user keeps context) and renders a diagnostics panel below it with five structured engine errors parsed from the \texttt {pdflatex} log. The \emph {Fix with AI} action sends the failed log and the source neighborhood to the AI orchestrator for a proposed patch.}}{60}{figure.caption.46}%
